-### Why not AutoWeightsLoader?
-
-`AutoWeightsLoader` requires checkpoint tensor names to match vLLM module names exactly. TAMM uses a completely different naming scheme (`transformer.tamm_model.layers.segment_0.layer_N` vs `model.layers.N`), and the segment flattening requires arithmetic (not static string substitution). A custom `load_weights` with `_remap_tamm_name()` is simpler and more explicit.
+- **Cut-off point**: layers 0тАУ34 are full QKV (segment 0); layers 35тАУ55 are Q-only (segment 1). The cut-off at layer 34 is the highest-index layer that *writes* its own KV cache тАФ it becomes the shared source for all 21 segment 1 layers. Layers beyond the cut-off have no `k_proj`/`v_proj` weights in the checkpoint at all.
+
+### AutoWeightsLoader vs custom `load_weights`
+
+| | `AutoWeightsLoader` | Custom `load_weights` + remap fn |
+|---|---|---|
+| **Use when** | Checkpoint names already match vLLM module names (e.g. a model ported directly from HF with identical layer naming) | Checkpoint uses a different naming scheme, requires arithmetic remapping, or has structural differences (fused vs split tensors) |
+| **How it works** | Iterates weights, matches by module path, calls `weight_loader` automatically | You write `_remap_name()`, iterate weights yourself, call `param.weight_loader(param, tensor)` explicitly |
+| **TAMM verdict** | тЭМ Not usable тАФ TAMM checkpoint uses `transformer.tamm_model.segment_0.layer_N` vs vLLM's `model.layers.N`; segment flattening requires arithmetic (35+M), not static string substitution | тЬЕ Used here тАФ explicit remap function handles all cases transparently |
+
+Rule of thumb: if you can express the name mapping as a one-line `str.replace()` chain, `AutoWeightsLoader` works. If it needs `int(m.group(1)) + 35` or conditional logic per segment, write a custom `load_weights`.
 
 ---
 
