+1. **RMSNorm** тАФ Divides by root-mean-square, scales by ╬│; no mean subtraction. ~10тАУ15% faster than LayerNorm with equivalent quality. Used 57├Ч in Qwen3: pre-Attention, pre-MLP, per Q/K head (prevents attention collapse), and final norm. Pre-Norm placement (norm before sub-block, not after residual) fixes gradient instability in deep networks.
+
+2. **GQA (Grouped Query Attention)** тАФ 8 KV heads shared by 16 Q heads; 2 Q heads per KV head. KV cache shrinks by `num_kv_heads/num_q_heads` (0.5├Ч here, 8├Ч for Llama 3 70B's 8/64 ratio). Quality loss is minimal because V is only linearly combined тАФ the KV heads don't need 1:1 correspondence with Q heads to preserve expressive power.
+
+3. **SwiGLU** тАФ `W_down(SiLU(W_gate(x)) ├Ч W_up(x))`. Gate and content are decoupled linear projections: gate learns *whether* a feature matters, up learns *what* it is. SiLU is smooth everywhere (non-zero gradient for x<0), preventing dying neurons. Intermediate size is ~8d/3 (not 4d) to keep total parameter count equal to a 2-matrix FFN.
+
+4. **RoPE** тАФ Rotates Q and K by position-dependent angles so `dot(Q_m, K_n)` depends only on relative distance `(mтИТn)`. Each of the d/2 dimension pairs rotates at frequency `╬╕с╡в = base^(тИТ2i/d)` тАФ fast frequencies distinguish nearby tokens, slow ones distinguish far-apart tokens. V is not rotated (no positional bias needed for the weighted sum). Zero extra parameters.
+
+5. **Tensor Parallelism tradeoffs** тАФ Megatron ColumnтЖТRow pattern: ColumnParallel (QKV, gate+up) needs zero communication; RowParallel (o_proj, down_proj) needs one all_reduce. Total: **2 all_reduces per layer**. Scaling cost: all_reduce latency grows with tp_size (more GPUs = larger collective). Benefit saturates when per-GPU compute < all_reduce latency тАФ typically tp_size тЙд 8 within a single NVLink node. Embedding uses all_reduce (sum); LM head uses gather+concat тАФ same shared weight, different collectives because one is a row-lookup and the other slices the vocabulary.
+
+6. **"Walk me through a decoder layer."** тАФ Input тЖТ RMSNorm тЖТ QKV projection (fused) тЖТ per-head norm тЖТ RoPE тЖТ flash attention (reads/writes KV cache) тЖТ output projection. Then RMSNorm тЖТ gate+up projection (fused) тЖТ SiLU gating тЖТ down projection. Residual connections wrap both sub-blocks.
+
+7. **"Why fuse QKV / gate+up?"** тАФ One large matmul is more efficient than multiple small ones on a GPU (better Tensor Core utilization, fewer kernel launches).
 
 8. **"What's the residual pattern?"** тАФ Fused add+norm: RMSNorm first adds previous output to running residual, saves un-normalized sum, then normalizes. Compiles to single kernel, preserves clean gradient path.
 
-9. **"Embedding and LM head share weights тАФ why different implementations?"** тАФ They do opposite operations: embedding is a row lookup (`weight[token_id]`), LM head is a matmul (`hidden @ weight.T`). On multi-GPU: embedding uses `all_reduce` (sum) because only one GPU has the real embedding, others contribute zeros. LM head uses `gather + concat` because each GPU computes logits for a different vocabulary slice тАФ summing them would mix scores for unrelated tokens.
+9. **"How does weight tying work?"** тАФ Embedding and LM head share the same `[151936, 1024]` tensor. Gradients from both ends accumulate into one `W.grad`. Saves ~293MB (fp16) and enforces geometric consistency: the vector that *represents* token T as input is the same vector used to *detect* token T as output.
 
