 1. **Walk me through a decoder layer.** Input тЖТ RMSNorm тЖТ QKV projection (fused) тЖТ per-head norm тЖТ RoPE тЖТ flash attention (reads/writes KV cache) тЖТ output projection. Then RMSNorm тЖТ gate+up projection (fused) тЖТ SiLU gating тЖТ down projection. Residual connections wrap both sub-blocks.
 
-2. **Explain GQA and its memory benefit.** Fewer KV heads than Q heads (8 vs 16 here). Multiple Q heads share one KV head. KV cache reduction factor = `num_kv_heads / num_q_heads` (0.5├Ч here, 8├Ч for Llama 3 70B with 8 KV heads / 64 Q heads). Minimal quality loss empirically.
-
-3. **RMSNorm vs LayerNorm trade-offs.** RMSNorm drops mean subtraction and the ╬▓ parameter тАФ ablations show re-centering is unnecessary for Transformers. Result: ~10тАУ15% faster, same quality. LayerNorm has ╬│+╬▓; RMSNorm has ╬│ only.
-
-4. **Why does Qwen3 add Q/K norm but not V norm?** Q and K participate in `QKс╡А / тИЪd_k` тАФ large magnitudes explode attention scores, saturating softmax and killing gradients. V is only weighted-summed; its magnitude doesn't affect score sharpness. Normalizing V would erase useful semantic magnitude for free.
-
-5. **What is RoPE and why multiple frequencies?** Rotates Q/K by position-dependent angles so `dot(Q_m, K_n)` depends only on relative distance `(mтИТn)`. Each dimension pair rotates at a different base frequency `╬╕с╡в = base^(тИТ2i/d)`. Like clock hands: fast frequencies distinguish nearby tokens, slow frequencies distinguish far-apart tokens. Zero extra parameters. V is not rotated.
-
-6. **What is SwiGLU and why does it outperform ReLU MLP?** `W_down(SiLU(W_gate(x)) * W_up(x))`. Gate learns to filter, up learns to represent тАФ decoupled projections. SiLU has non-zero gradient everywhere (minimum тЙИ тИТ0.28 at xтЙИтИТ1.28), preventing dying neurons that plague ReLU at scale. Parameter count stays equal by using `intermediate = 8d/3 тЙИ 2.67d` instead of 4d.
-
-7. **Why fuse QKV / gate+up into one matmul?** One large matmul is more efficient than two/three small ones: better Tensor Core utilization, fewer kernel launches, one memory round-trip for the input activation.
-
-8. **Explain the TP communication pattern per decoder layer.** Megatron ColumnтЖТRow pattern: ColumnParallel (QKV, gate+up) needs zero communication тАФ each GPU independently computes its output slice. RowParallel (o_proj, down_proj) needs one all_reduce to sum partial results. Total: **2 all_reduces per layer**.
-
-9. **Embedding and LM head share weights тАФ why different collective ops on multi-GPU?** Embedding uses `all_reduce` (sum) because only one GPU has the real embedding row, others contribute zeros. LM head uses `gather + concat` because each GPU computes logits for a different vocabulary slice тАФ summing would mix scores for unrelated tokens.
+2. **GQA: what it is, why it matters, and the exact memory formula.** Fewer KV heads than Q heads (8 vs 16 here). Multiple Q heads share one KV head. KV cache shrinks by factor `num_kv_heads / num_q_heads` тАФ 0.5├Ч here, 8├Ч for Llama 3 70B (8 KV / 64 Q heads). Quality loss is minimal because KV heads still carry full `head_dim=64` information; only the *number* of distinct K/V representations is reduced. MQA is the extreme case (1 KV head), GQA is the generalisation.
+
+3. **RMSNorm vs LayerNorm тАФ trade-offs and why RMSNorm won.** RMSNorm drops mean subtraction and the ╬▓ parameter. Ablations show re-centering is unnecessary for Transformers тАФ the residual stream already has zero mean at init. Result: ~10тАУ15% faster, same quality. LayerNorm has ╬│+╬▓ (2 ├Ч hidden_dim params); RMSNorm has ╬│ only (1 ├Ч). Pre-Norm placement (before each sub-block) is also critical: it keeps the residual stream un-normalized, giving gradients a clean path back to the embedding.
+
+4. **Why Q/K norm but not V norm in Qwen3?** Q and K participate in `QKс╡А / тИЪd_k` тАФ heads with large L2 norm explode attention scores, saturating softmax and zeroing gradients (attention collapse). V is only weighted-summed by attention weights; its magnitude doesn't affect score sharpness. Normalizing V would destroy useful semantic magnitude information for no benefit.
+
+5. **SwiGLU mechanics and why it outperforms ReLU FFN.** `output = W_down( SiLU(W_gate(x)) ├Ч W_up(x) )`. Gate and content paths are decoupled learnable projections: gate learns *whether* a feature fires, up learns *what* the feature is. SiLU has non-zero gradient everywhere (minimum тЙИ тИТ0.28 at xтЙИтИТ1.28), eliminating dying neurons that plague ReLU at scale. To keep parameter count equal to the original 4├Ч FFN (2 matrices), SwiGLU uses 3 matrices with `intermediate = 8d/3 тЙИ 2.67d`; Qwen3 rounds to 3├Ч (3072/1024). SiLU and element-wise multiply are per-element ops, so TP sharding is trivially correct тАФ unlike softmax which needs a global denominator.
+
+6. **Explain the TP ColumnтЖТRow pattern and communication cost.** ColumnParallel (QKV, gate+up): each GPU independently computes its output slice тАФ zero communication. RowParallel (o_proj, down_proj): each GPU holds input_size/tp rows of W and produces a partial sum; one `all_reduce` recombines. Total: **2 all_reduces per decoder layer**. With tp=2, attention splits Q into 8 heads per GPU and KV into 4 heads per GPU; GQA ratio is preserved per-GPU.
+
+7. **Why fuse QKV / gate+up into one matmul?** One large matmul beats two/three small ones: better Tensor Core utilization, fewer kernel launches, one memory round-trip for the input activation. `SiluAndMul` then uses `@torch.compile` to fuse the chunk + SiLU + multiply into a single GPU kernel.
+
+8. **Embedding vs LM head: same weights, different collective ops тАФ why?** Embedding uses `all_reduce` (sum): vocabulary rows are sharded, so only one GPU has the real embedding for a given token, others contribute zeros тАФ summing reconstructs the correct vector. LM head uses `gather + concat`: each GPU computes logits for its vocabulary slice тАФ summing would mix scores for *different* tokens, corrupting the distribution.
+
+9. **What is RoPE and why multiple frequencies?** Rotates Q/K by position-dependent angles so `dot(Q_m, K_n)` depends only on relative distance `(mтИТn)`. Each of the `d/2` dimension pairs rotates at `╬╕с╡в = base^(тИТ2i/d)`. Fast frequencies distinguish nearby tokens; slow frequencies distinguish distant ones тАФ analogous to clock hands. Zero extra parameters; V is not rotated because it is summed, not dot-producted.
 
