+3. **"GQA vs MHA vs MQA тАФ how do you choose?"** тАФ All three are the same attention math; they differ only in how many KV heads are shared. MHA (16Q/16KV): maximum quality, maximum KV cache (4096 bytes/token/layer for Qwen3). GQA (16Q/8KV): halves KV cache to 2048 bytes/token/layer with minimal quality loss тАФ the empirical sweet spot used by Qwen3, LLaMA-3, Mistral. MQA (16Q/1KV): 16├Ч smaller cache but measurable quality degradation on long-context tasks. Choose GQA for production LLMs; MQA only under extreme memory constraints; MHA when reproducing older architectures (GPT-2 era).
+
+4. **"Prefill vs decode: different kernels, why?"** тАФ Same attention math, opposite bottleneck. Prefill: all N tokens' Q,K,V available, compute scales O(N┬▓┬╖d_k) тЖТ compute-bound тЖТ `flash_attn_varlen_func` with packed variable-length sequences for continuous batching. Decode: Q is 1 token but must read all N cached K,V from HBM тЖТ memory-bound тЖТ `flash_attn_with_kvcache` with paged block_table addressing. Optimizations target the actual bottleneck: fused kernels for prefill, PagedAttention + speculative decoding for decode.
+
+5. **"Flash Attention vs standard attention тАФ when would you choose each?"** тАФ Standard attention materializes the full [N,N] score matrix in HBM: O(N┬▓) memory, simple to implement, fine for N<512. Flash Attention tiles Q,K,V in SRAM, never materializing [N,N]: O(N) memory, ~3├Ч faster for N>1K due to fewer HBM reads, required for long-context (N=32K+). Choose Flash Attention for any production inference or training with sequences >512 tokens; standard only for debugging or when tiling constraints make Flash impractical (e.g., very small head_dim).
 
