-
-2. **GQA: what it is, why it matters, and the exact memory formula.** Fewer KV heads than Q heads (8 vs 16 here). Multiple Q heads share one KV head. KV cache shrinks by factor `num_kv_heads / num_q_heads` тАФ 0.5├Ч here, 8├Ч for Llama 3 70B (8 KV / 64 Q heads). Quality loss is minimal because KV heads still carry full `head_dim=64` information; only the *number* of distinct K/V representations is reduced. MQA is the extreme case (1 KV head), GQA is the generalisation.
-
-3. **RMSNorm vs LayerNorm тАФ trade-offs and why RMSNorm won.** RMSNorm drops mean subtraction and the ╬▓ parameter. Ablations show re-centering is unnecessary for Transformers тАФ the residual stream already has zero mean at init. Result: ~10тАУ15% faster, same quality. LayerNorm has ╬│+╬▓ (2 ├Ч hidden_dim params); RMSNorm has ╬│ only (1 ├Ч). Pre-Norm placement (before each sub-block) is also critical: it keeps the residual stream un-normalized, giving gradients a clean path back to the embedding.
-
-4. **Why Q/K norm but not V norm in Qwen3?** Q and K participate in `QKс╡А / тИЪd_k` тАФ heads with large L2 norm explode attention scores, saturating softmax and zeroing gradients (attention collapse). V is only weighted-summed by attention weights; its magnitude doesn't affect score sharpness. Normalizing V would destroy useful semantic magnitude information for no benefit.
-
-5. **SwiGLU mechanics and why it outperforms ReLU FFN.** `output = W_down( SiLU(W_gate(x)) ├Ч W_up(x) )`. Gate and content paths are decoupled learnable projections: gate learns *whether* a feature fires, up learns *what* the feature is. SiLU has non-zero gradient everywhere (minimum тЙИ тИТ0.28 at xтЙИтИТ1.28), eliminating dying neurons that plague ReLU at scale. To keep parameter count equal to the original 4├Ч FFN (2 matrices), SwiGLU uses 3 matrices with `intermediate = 8d/3 тЙИ 2.67d`; Qwen3 rounds to 3├Ч (3072/1024). SiLU and element-wise multiply are per-element ops, so TP sharding is trivially correct тАФ unlike softmax which needs a global denominator.
-
-6. **Explain the TP ColumnтЖТRow pattern and communication cost.** ColumnParallel (QKV, gate+up): each GPU independently computes its output slice тАФ zero communication. RowParallel (o_proj, down_proj): each GPU holds input_size/tp rows of W and produces a partial sum; one `all_reduce` recombines. Total: **2 all_reduces per decoder layer**. With tp=2, attention splits Q into 8 heads per GPU and KV into 4 heads per GPU; GQA ratio is preserved per-GPU.
-
