--- a/ml-systems/rotary-position-embedding.md
+++ b/ml-systems/rotary-position-embedding.md
@@ -277,6 +277,8 @@
 5. **Why is V not rotated?** Position only needs to affect attention weights (who attends to whom), not the content transmitted. Rotating V would inject position bias into the output values unnecessarily.
 
 6. **How does RoPE extend to long contexts?** Increase `base` (slows all frequencies, extends unique-position range), or use YaRN / LongRoPE to rescale frequencies non-uniformly at inference time without retraining.
+
+7. **When would you choose ALiBi vs RoPE for long-context?** Prefer **ALiBi** when you need strong out-of-the-box extrapolation beyond training length with minimal tuning тАФ its fixed linear distance penalty guarantees monotone decay of attention to distant tokens, which works well for tasks with local dependencies (e.g. language modelling, summarisation). Prefer **RoPE** when the task requires genuine long-range dependencies (e.g. retrieval, multi-document QA, code with distant cross-references) тАФ ALiBi's hard penalty actively suppresses long-range attention, whereas RoPE lets Q/K weights learn to attend far if the data requires it. RoPE also composes naturally with KV-cache and GQA; ALiBi requires no rotations so it has slightly simpler kernels, but it cannot benefit from frequency-scaling tricks (YaRN, LongRoPE) that give RoPE a clear path to 1M+ token contexts.
 ---
 
